New Classes of Set-Sequential Trees

Louis Golowich MIT PRIMES, Department of Mathematics, MIT, 77 Massachusetts Ave., Cambridge, MA 02139. Email: louis.golowich@gmail.com.    Chiheon Kim Department of Mathematics, MIT, 77 Massachusetts Ave., Cambridge, MA 02139. Email: chiheonk@math.mit.edu.
Abstract

A graph is called set-sequential if its vertices can be labeled with distinct nonzero vectors in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} such that when each edge is labeled with the sum(mod2)pmod2\pmod{2} of its vertices, every nonzero vector in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} is the label for either a single vertex or a single edge. We resolve certain cases of a conjecture of Balister, Győri, and Schelp in order to show many new classes of trees to be set-sequential. We show that all caterpillars T𝑇T of diameter k𝑘k such that k≤18𝑘18k\leq 18 or |V​(T)|≥2k−1𝑉𝑇superscript2𝑘1|V(T)|\geq 2^{k-1} are set-sequential, where T𝑇T has only odd-degree vertices and |T|=2n−1𝑇superscript2𝑛1|T|=2^{n-1} for some positive integer n𝑛n. We also present a new method of recursively constructing set-sequential trees.

1 Introduction

A labeling of a graph G𝐺G with a set S𝑆S of labels is any function from the vertices and edges of G𝐺G to S𝑆S. A graph is called set-sequential if there exists a labeling of its vertices with distinct nonzero vectors in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} such that when each edge is labeled with the sum(mod2)pmod2\pmod{2} of its vertices, every nonzero vector in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} is used exactly once as a label for either a vertex or for an edge; this definition is generally attributed to [1]. As a direct consequence of this definition, a graph G𝐺G can be set-sequential only if |V​(G)|+|E​(G)|=2n−1𝑉𝐺𝐸𝐺superscript2𝑛1|V(G)|+|E(G)|=2^{n}-1 for some n𝑛n.

Much work on the problem of classifying set-sequential graphs has been focused on trees. Of particular interest are caterpillar trees, defined to be any tree containing some path, called the center path, from which every vertex has distance at most 1. It is often useful to classify caterpillars by the diameter, which is the largest distance between any two vertices in a connected graph. In the case of caterpillars, the diameter gives the length of the center path.

Abhishek and Agustine [2] showed that all caterpillars of diameter at most 4 with only odd-degree vertices, and with 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices for some n𝑛n, are set-sequential. Abhishek [3] extended this result to caterpillars of diameter 5. Mehta and Vijayakumar [4] showed that all paths of length 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} are set-sequential if n≥5𝑛5n\geq 5. Hegde [5] showed that no graph with exactly 1 or 2 vertices of even degree is set-sequential. However, no similar restriction is known for graphs with only odd-degree vertices, a fact motivating in the following conjecture. (This conjecture appears to have been proposed before, but we were unable to find a citation, so we restate it here.)

Conjecture 1.1.

All trees with only odd-degree vertices and with 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n} vertices for some integer n𝑛n are set-sequential.

Our results in this paper mark progress towards Conjecture 1.1, and thus we mostly focus on trees with only odd-degree vertices.

Balister, Győri, and Schelp [6] proposed a general method to generate set-sequential trees by adding 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} pendant edges to a set-sequential tree with 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices. Specifically, consider a set-sequential tree T𝑇T with 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices. Then define T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} to be a tree with 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n} vertices that is obtained by adding 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} pendant edges to T𝑇T, and let the i𝑖ith new pendant edge for 1≤i≤2n−11𝑖superscript2𝑛11\leq i\leq 2^{n-1} be attached to the vertex in T𝑇T labeled visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}. The following structure for a set-sequential labeling of T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} was proposed in [6], and is illustrated in Figure 1. Append 00 to the beginning of the label of every vertex and edge that was already in T𝑇T (every vertex and edge that is not from a new pendant edge), and let the i𝑖ith new pendant edge consist of a vertex labeled 1​pi1subscript𝑝𝑖1p_{i} and an edge 1​qi1subscript𝑞𝑖1q_{i}, where a​b𝑎𝑏ab denotes the concatenation of a𝑎a and b𝑏b. Then for T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} to be set-sequential, the following two conditions must hold by definition:

  • •

    The set of all pisubscript𝑝𝑖p_{i}’s and qisubscript𝑞𝑖q_{i}’s for 1≤i≤2n−11𝑖superscript2𝑛11\leq i\leq 2^{n-1} consists of all vectors in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n}.

  • •

    For all 1≤i≤2n−11𝑖superscript2𝑛11\leq i\leq 2^{n-1}, it holds that 1​pi+0​vi=1​qi1subscript𝑝𝑖0subscript𝑣𝑖1subscript𝑞𝑖1p_{i}+0v_{i}=1q_{i}, or equivalently, pi+qi=visubscript𝑝𝑖subscript𝑞𝑖subscript𝑣𝑖p_{i}+q_{i}=v_{i}.

It follows by these constraints that if n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2, then

(1)

It was conjectured in [6] that for any choice of the visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}’s satisfying (1), there always exists a choice of the pisubscript𝑝𝑖p_{i}’s and qisubscript𝑞𝑖q_{i}’s for which the two conditions above hold, as formalized below.

Conjecture 1.2 ([6]).

For any 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} non-zero vectors v1,…,v2n−1∈𝔽2nsubscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1superscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}\in\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} with n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2 and ∑i=12n−1vi=0superscriptsubscript𝑖1superscript2𝑛1subscript𝑣𝑖0\sum_{i=1}^{2^{n-1}}v_{i}=0, there exists a partition of 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} into pairs of vectors (pi,qi)subscript𝑝𝑖subscript𝑞𝑖(p_{i},q_{i}) for 1≤i≤2n−11𝑖superscript2𝑛11\leq i\leq 2^{n-1} such that vi=pi+qisubscript𝑣𝑖subscript𝑝𝑖subscript𝑞𝑖v_{i}=p_{i}+q_{i} for all i𝑖i.

Conjecture 1.2 was shown in [6] to hold if n≤5𝑛5n\leq 5 or if v1=⋯=v2n−2subscript𝑣1⋯subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛2v_{1}=\dots=v_{2^{n-2}} and v2​i−1=v2​isubscript𝑣2𝑖1subscript𝑣2𝑖v_{2i-1}=v_{2i} for all 1≤i≤2n−21𝑖superscript2𝑛21\leq i\leq 2^{n-2}.

In this paper, we resolve additional cases of Conjecture 1.2 in order to show the set-sequentialness of new classes of trees. We resolve the conjecture in cases where either the dimension of the span of the vectors v1,…,v2n−1subscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}} or the number of distinct vectors visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i} is restricted. We then show that all caterpillars T𝑇T with only odd-degree vertices of diameter k𝑘k such that k≤18𝑘18k\leq 18 or |V​(T)|≥2k−1𝑉𝑇superscript2𝑘1|V(T)|\geq 2^{k-1} are set-sequential, assuming that T𝑇T has 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices for some positive integer n𝑛n. We also present a new method of constructing a set-sequential tree by connecting four copies of an existing set-sequential tree, which enables us to prove the set-sequentialness of a broader class of trees that is not covered by the method presented in [6].

The organization of this paper is as follows. In Section 2, we partially prove Conjecture 1.2 by placing additional restrictions on the dimension of the span of v1,…,v2n−1subscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}, or on the number of distinct vectors visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}. In Section 3.1, we apply the results from Section 2 to showing new classes of trees, and specifically caterpillars, to be set-sequential. In Section 3.2, we present an alternative method of constructing set-sequential trees. We provide concluding remarks in Section 4.

Because Conjecture 1.2 was shown in [6] to hold in 𝔽22,…,𝔽25superscriptsubscript𝔽22…superscriptsubscript𝔽25\mathbb{F}_{2}^{2},\dots,\mathbb{F}_{2}^{5}, the following corollary directly follows from Proposition 2.2.

Corollary 2.2.1.

For any 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} nonzero vectors v1,…,v2n−1∈𝔽2nsubscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1superscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}\in\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} such that ∑i=12n−1vi=0superscriptsubscript𝑖1superscript2𝑛1subscript𝑣𝑖0\sum_{i=1}^{2^{n-1}}v_{i}=0 and dim(span⁡{v1,…,v2n−1})≤5dimensionspansubscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛15\dim(\operatorname{span}\{v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}\})\leq 5, there exists a partition of 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} into pairs (pi,qi)subscript𝑝𝑖subscript𝑞𝑖(p_{i},q_{i}) such that pi+qi=visubscript𝑝𝑖subscript𝑞𝑖subscript𝑣𝑖p_{i}+q_{i}=v_{i} for all 1≤i≤2n−11𝑖superscript2𝑛11\leq i\leq 2^{n-1}.

As a result of Corollary 2.2.1, set-sequential trees can easily be constructed in the following manner. For any given 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1}-vertex set-sequential tree T𝑇T, consider any tree T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} obtained by adding a total of 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} pendant edges to at most 5 distinct vertices in T𝑇T, such that each vertex receives an even number of new pendant edges. By using stars and caterpillars of diameter 4 or 5, which are known to be set-sequential, as base cases, this method already provides a way of inductively showing the set-sequentialness of infinitely many trees. We explore this idea in more detail in Section 3.1.

In many cases, when partitioning the visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}’s into the subsets Vjsubscript𝑉𝑗V_{j} as in the proof of Proposition 2.2, there exists a partition for which the span of the elements of each subset has dimension less than the dimension of the span of all the visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}’s. This idea is applied in the result below, which proves another restricted case of Conjecture 1.2.

Lemma 2.3.

Let v1,…,v2n−1∈𝔽2nsubscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1superscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}\in\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n} satisfy v2​i−1=v2​isubscript𝑣2𝑖1subscript𝑣2𝑖v_{2i-1}=v_{2i} for all 1≤i≤2n−21𝑖superscript2𝑛21\leq i\leq 2^{n-2} and let there be at most l<n𝑙𝑛l<n distinct vectors u1,…,ulsubscript𝑢1…subscript𝑢𝑙u_{1},\dots,u_{l} among the visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}’s, so that each visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i} is equal to some value in u1,…,ulsubscript𝑢1…subscript𝑢𝑙u_{1},\dots,u_{l}. Proof.

We show the result through induction on n𝑛n. For the base case, Conjecture 1.2 is true for 𝔽22superscriptsubscript𝔽22\mathbb{F}_{2}^{2}. Otherwise, if l≥3𝑙3l\geq 3, assume without loss of generality that neither u1subscript𝑢1u_{1} nor u2subscript𝑢2u_{2} occur more than 2n−2superscript2𝑛22^{n-2} times among the visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}’s. Although the condition of having an even number of copies of each vector may seem arbitrary, it is in fact motivated by set-sequential trees. We mostly focus on trees with only odd-degree vertices due to Conjecture 1.1, and therefore adding an odd number of pendant edges to a vertex, which corresponds to having an odd number of copies of some vector visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}, is often not useful. Furthermore, as the sum of a vector and itself is 0 in 𝔽2nsuperscriptsubscript𝔽2𝑛\mathbb{F}_{2}^{n}, the condition that ∑i=12n−1vi=0superscriptsubscript𝑖1superscript2𝑛1subscript𝑣𝑖0\sum_{i=1}^{2^{n-1}}v_{i}=0 is automatically met, so we can use our progress on Conjecture 1.2 to inductively produce set-sequential trees without having to keep track of the actual labels of the vertices.

We now improve the result in Corollary 2.2.1 by showing that Conjecture 1.2 holds if each vector occurs an even number of times and if dim(span⁡{v1,…,v2n−1})≤n/2dimensionspansubscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1𝑛2\dim(\operatorname{span}\{v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}\})\leq n/2, thereby improving a constant bound on the dimension of the span of the vectors to a linear bound.

Now we prove a relatively restricted case of Conjecture 1.2, which can be used to prove the set-sequentialness of many small trees. We also generalize our proof in additional results below.

The following corollary directly follows from Proposition 2.5, as Conjecture 1.2 was verified to hold in 𝔽25superscriptsubscript𝔽25\mathbb{F}_{2}^{5} in [6].

Corollary 2.5.1.

3 New classes of set-sequential trees

In this section, we apply Theorem 2.8 to show the set-sequentialness of many new classes of caterpillars. We then present a new inductive method for generating set-sequential trees.

To begin, we present the following lemma, which provides an application of the cases of Theorem 2.8 for which vectors can occur an odd number of times among v1,…,v2n−1subscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣superscript2𝑛1v_{1},\dots,v_{2^{n-1}}. 3.1 Caterpillars with only odd-degree vertices

In this section, we show that any caterpillar T𝑇T of diameter k𝑘k with only odd-degree vertices such that k≤18𝑘18k\leq 18 or 2k−1≤|V​(T)|superscript2𝑘1𝑉𝑇2^{k-1}\leq|V(T)| is set-sequential.

Here, we only discuss trees with 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices for some positive integer n𝑛n, unless explicitly stated otherwise. Abhishek and Agustine [2] showed that a caterpillar with diameter 4 is set-sequential if and only if each vertex has odd degree. Abhishek [3] extended this result by showing the same characterization holds for set-sequential caterpillars of diameter 5.

The motivation behind Conjecture 1.2 presented in [6] is easily applied to show that the conjecture, if true, would imply the existence of a finite set of caterpillars of some given diameter k𝑘k for which if these caterpillars are set-sequential, then all caterpillars of diameter k𝑘k with only odd-degree vertices are set-sequential. This statement is not extended to caterpillars with even-degree vertices because infinite classes of such caterpillars that are not set-sequential are shown to exist in [5]. The cases of the conjecture that we prove above are sufficient to show that such a finite set exists, although this finite set would be significantly smaller if the entire conjecture were known to be true. However, for sufficiently small n𝑛n, we verify below that all graphs in this finite set are set-sequential.

Following the notation of Abhishek and Agustine [2], let T​[d1,…,dk]𝑇subscript𝑑1…subscript𝑑𝑘T[d_{1},\dots,d_{k}] denote the caterpillar with a k𝑘k-vertex center path such that the i𝑖ith center path vertex has degree disubscript𝑑𝑖d_{i}. This notation gives some freedom in expressing caterpillars; we typically use the unique form such that di≥2subscript𝑑𝑖2d_{i}\geq 2 for all 1≤i≤k1𝑖𝑘1\leq i\leq k, so that the caterpillar has diameter k+1𝑘1k+1. As a necessary exception, we use T​[1]𝑇delimited-[]1T[1] to denote the graph consisting of a single edge. In the result below, we apply the first two cases in Theorem 3.2 in order to show that all caterpillars with diameter at most 18 are set-sequential.

To illustrate the validity of the assertions above, we explain how the set-sequentialness of T​[3,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,3]𝑇3332222223T[3,3,3,2,2,2,2,2,2,3] implies the set-sequentialness of all caterpillars with no even-degree vertices of diameter 11, 12, or 13; an analagous argument applies to the other statements. From here, we proceed through induction. ∎

Because the result above is ultimately dependent on the fact that Conjecture 1.2 has been verified for n≤5𝑛5n\leq 5, in order to extend the upper bound of 18 on the caterpillar diameter, it would be necessary to either verify that the conjecture holds for larger n𝑛n, or to verify that many more caterpillars serving as base cases are set-sequential. However, by applying Case 3 of Theorem 3.2, we show below that all caterpillars with sufficiently many vertices, and no even-degree vertices, of any given diameter are set-sequential.

Theorem 3.4.

For all k≥0𝑘0k\geq 0, all caterpillars of diameter k+1𝑘1k+1 that have only odd-degree vertices and have at least 2ksuperscript2𝑘2^{k} vertices, with 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n} total vertices for some n𝑛n, are set-sequential.

Proof.

We show the result by induction. For the base case, note that the result holds for k≤1𝑘1k\leq 1 by Theorem 3.3. For the inductive step, let k≥2𝑘2k\geq 2, and assume that the result holds for all caterpillars of diameter at most k𝑘k. We now show that any caterpillar T′=T​[d1,…,dk]superscript𝑇′𝑇subscript𝑑1…subscript𝑑𝑘T^{\prime}=T[d_{1},\dots,d_{k}] of diameter k+1𝑘1k+1 with 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n} vertices is set-sequential if 2n≥2ksuperscript2𝑛superscript2𝑘2^{n}\geq 2^{k}. First note that T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} has 2n−k≥2n−1+(k−2)superscript2𝑛𝑘superscript2𝑛1𝑘22^{n}-k\geq 2^{n-1}+(k-2) pendant edges, so it is possible to remove 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} pendant edges from T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} while maintaining the property that each vertex has odd degree. By assuming without loss of generality that d1≤dksubscript𝑑1subscript𝑑𝑘d_{1}\leq d_{k}, then because (d1−1)+(dk−1)<|E​(T′)|=2n−1subscript𝑑11subscript𝑑𝑘1𝐸superscript𝑇′superscript2𝑛1(d_{1}-1)+(d_{k}-1)<|E(T^{\prime})|=2^{n}-1, it follows that d1−1<2n−1subscript𝑑11superscript2𝑛1d_{1}-1<2^{n-1}. Therefore, there exists a graph T𝑇T obtained by removing all d1−1subscript𝑑11d_{1}-1 pendant edges stemming from the first vertex in the path of T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime}, and some additional pendant edges, such that T𝑇T has 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} vertices, all with odd degree. Because vertices in the path have odd degree before and after the removal, each of these vertices lost an even number of pendant edges. Furthermore, by construction T𝑇T has diameter either k𝑘k or k−1𝑘1k-1, and |V​(T)|=2n−1≥2k−1≥2k−2𝑉𝑇superscript2𝑛1superscript2𝑘1superscript2𝑘2|V(T)|=2^{n-1}\geq 2^{k-1}\geq 2^{k-2}, so therefore T𝑇T is set-sequential by the inductive hypothesis. It follows that T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} is set-sequential by Case 3 of Theorem 3.2. ∎

The argument used to show Theorem 3.4 can be extended to other general classes of trees. Intuitively, it can be used to show the set-sequentialness of trees with sufficiently many pendant edges, or vertices with degree 1.

3.2 Attaching copies of set-sequential trees

Although Theorem 3.2 provides a powerful way to inductively produce set-sequential trees, it is most useful for showing that trees with many vertices for a fixed diameter are set-sequential. Likewise, this method is not very useful for finding trees with relatively large diameters and few vertices, such as trees consisting of a long path with a few small offshoots. However, these types of trees containing long paths can serve as base cases in induction using Theorem 3.2, and are therefore of interest. Mehta and Vijayakumar [4] show that all paths with at least 16 vertices are set-sequential. Below, we use a similar method of proof as in [4], but we show a much more general result, which applies to all trees as opposed to only paths.

Let Z𝑍Z be a set-sequential path with vertices u𝑢u and v𝑣v of degree 1, and let k𝑘k be defined so that Z𝑍Z has (k+1)𝑘1(k+1)/2 vertices. For a set-sequential tree T𝑇T with x𝑥x odd-degree vertices and y𝑦y even-degree vertices, Theorem 3.5 shows the set-sequentialness of at least one tree T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} with 4​x−64𝑥64x-6 odd-degree vertices and 4​y+64𝑦64y+6 even-degree vertices. However, if y=0𝑦0y=0, Case 1 of Theorem 3.2 is easily used to create a tree T′′superscript𝑇′′T^{\prime\prime} with twice the number of vertices as T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} containing no even-degree vertices. Furthermore, Case 3 of the corollary can be used to create such a tree T′′superscript𝑇′′T^{\prime\prime} even if T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} has more than 6 even-degree vertices, as long as T′superscript𝑇′T^{\prime} has sufficiently many vertices. Using this idea, it is easy to see that Theorem 3.5 can be used to construct sequences of trees, which may be caterpillars, such that the diameter grows nearly linearly with the number of vertices. Specifically, such sequences would be constructed by repeatedly applying Theorem 3.5 t𝑡t times and Theorem 3.2 one time for some integer t𝑡t, beginning from some base tree.

Another motivation for Theorem 3.5 was to find a caterpillar Tksubscript𝑇𝑘T_{k} of diameter k𝑘k with at most 2​k2𝑘2k vertices such that T𝑇T is set-sequential for as many positive integers k𝑘k as possible. Each such set-sequential caterpillar Tksubscript𝑇𝑘T_{k} could serve as a base case for showing the set-sequentialness of all caterpillars of diameter k𝑘k with no even-degree vertices through induction if Conjecture 1.2 were known to be true, or if a sufficiently strong subset of the conjecture were known to hold. Theorem 3.5 succeeds in showing the existence of infinitely many such caterpillars Tksubscript𝑇𝑘T_{k} other than paths, which were shown to be set-sequential in [4]. For example, the theorem can be repeatedly applied beginning with the star with 3 leaves in order to show that there exists a set-sequential caterpillar Tksubscript𝑇𝑘T_{k} of diameter k𝑘k with at most 2​k2𝑘2k vertices for all integers k𝑘k that can be written in the form k=3⋅4c−1𝑘⋅3superscript4𝑐1k=3\cdot 4^{c}-1 for some nonnegative integer c𝑐c.

4 Concluding Remarks

In this paper, we investigate the problem of classifying set-sequential trees. We resolve many restricted cases of Conjecture 1.2, which Balister, Győri, and Schelp [6] introduced as a potential general method for showing trees to be set-sequential. We then apply our progress on Conjecture 1.2 to show the set-sequentialness of many new classes of caterpillars. We also introduce a new method for constructing set-sequential trees that can be applied to many classes of trees for which the method of [6] is not useful.

Many of our results are motivated by Conjecture 1.1, which states that all trees with only odd-degree vertices, and with 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n} vertices for some nonnegative integer n𝑛n, are set-sequential. In Section 3.1, we resolve certain cases of this conjecture by applying the idea introduced in [6] of generating set-sequential trees by adding 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1} pendant edges to a 2n−1superscript2𝑛12^{n-1}-vertex tree. However, this method cannot prove a tree to be set-sequential for which fewer than half of the vertices have degree 1. With respect to this limitation, Theorem 3.5 is particularly interesting, as it shows the set-sequentialness of classes of trees with arbitrarily few vertices of degree 1. We suggest that additional similar results could help approach the problem of showing the set-sequentialness of all trees with only odd-degree vertices.
